This paper focuses on developing an automated metric to evaluate dialogue quality, which falls under the category of natural language processing and computational linguistics (cs.CL). The paper also introduces new feature sets and machine learning models to estimate user satisfaction, which involves artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and machine learning (cs.LG). Additionally, the paper discusses the generalizability of the annotation scheme to conversations spanning multiple domains, which relates to the field of cybernetics (cs.CY). Finally, the paper emphasizes the importance of optimizing data-driven dialogue management, which involves human-computer interaction (cs.HC).
